re but also generating ~Rs. 3000 crores in revenue compared to Titan Eyewear's ~Rs. 700 Crores.<br><br>Here are the 4 key strategies Peyush Bansal used &#128071;<br><br><strong>1/ Solved for Accessibility</strong><br>Lenskart understood that eyewear is a highly "touch and feel" category, where you need a high physical footprint for conversion. Right now they have 2000+ stores spread across ~230 cities while Titan Eye+ only has ~1000 stores in almost the same number of cities.<br><br>More Stores&#8594; More Customer Walk-Ins &#8594; More Trust &#8594; More conversions on the mobile app.<br><br><strong>2/ Solved for Affordability</strong><br>Peyush Bansal wanted to be the "Maruti" of the Indian eyewear segment. And to be a Maruti, he had to make sure that products were affordable.<br><br>Used offers like:<br>&#9989; One + One free<br>&#9989;&nbsp;First frame free<br>&#9989; Gold membership<br>&#9989;&nbsp;Starting from Rs. 500<br><br>They followed the principles of value-based pricing to capture the highly sensitive Indian market.<br><br><strong>3/ Solved for Awareness</strong><br>Lenskart is a rare startup that has a broad range of popular "in-house" brands. From John Jacobs to Vincent Chase, the company has targeted different customers with multiple options in different price ranges.<br><br>They generated high "word of mouth" through:<br>&#10004;&#65039;Virtual Trials through application<br>&#10004;&#65039;Introducing advanced features like Blue Cut<br>&#10004;&#65039;Collaborating with mainstream celebrities like Katrina Kaif &amp; Karan Johar<br><br><strong>4/ Solved for Unit-Economics</strong><br>Lenskart mastered its supply chains &amp; inventory management by using AI for:<br><br>&#9989;Stock levels<br>&#9989;Real-time sales<br>&#9989;Inventory transit<br>&#9989;Product performance<br><br>But, there's more &#10024;<br>In the latest episode of GrowthX Wireframe, we dive into all these points &amp; so much more. </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;ur